<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="179" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1807,2013]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,1041]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="179" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,384,1807,1834]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Female macroptera.</emphasis>
Body bicoloured (
<figureCitation box="[595,664,1807,1834]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); head and pterothorax brown; pronotum yellow with blotch shaded; metanotum pale at posterior third (
<figureCitation box="[542,611,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); abdominal segment I yellowish brown with antecostal ridge interrupted medially, II–III brown, VII–IX brown, X yellow with brown infusion; antecostal ridges on tergites II–VII complete and dark brown; antennal segments I–III yellow, IV yellow with apical brown infusion, V–VIII brown. Fore wing brown with a pale sub-basal area, basal ¾ of clavus brown (
<figureCitation box="[832,917,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); all femora, tibiae and tarsi brown. Antennae 8-segmented (
<figureCitation box="[311,395,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Head wider than long, with sculpture lines within ocellar triangle, with internal markings; occipital apodeme touching posterior margin of eyes; ocellar setae III placed inside ocellar triangle; post-occipital area with transverse striations; three pairs of postocular setae along posterior inner margin of eyes, all subequal and subequal to ocellar setae III (
<figureCitation box="[432,499,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Pronotum transversely reticulate with internal markings; blotch well defined, transversely reticulate with internal markings, concave at anterior margin, posterior margin merged with pronotal posterior margin; short posteroangular setae; 3 pairs of posteromarginal setae (
<figureCitation box="[930,1000,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum transversely striate, with internal markings, median pair of setae ahead of sub-median pair well anterior to posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1290,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Metanotum sculptured transversely anteromedially, longitudinally at each side, irregularly reticulate at middle, with internal markings; median setae a little behind anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[709,777,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Fore wing first vein with continuous row of setae, second vein without setae (
<figureCitation box="[363,443,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergites I–VI medially without marginal microtrichia; VII–VIII with complete row of marginal microtrichia; tergites I–II with discal microtrichia laterally, III–V with discal microtrichia medially and laterally (
<figureCitation box="[301,488,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–19" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–19. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (13) Female abdominal tergites IX–X; (14) Abdominal tergite III; (15) Abdominal tergite VI; (16) Pore plate on male abdominal sternites VI–VII; (17) Abdominal tergite VIII; (18) Abdominal tergite V; (19) Abdominal tergite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920164/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Figs 14, 18 &amp; 19</figureCitation>
), VI–VIII fully covered with discal mirotrichia; IX with no discal microtrichia; X with discal microtrichia posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[496,577,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–19" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–19. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (13) Female abdominal tergites IX–X; (14) Abdominal tergite III; (15) Abdominal tergite VI; (16) Pore plate on male abdominal sternites VI–VII; (17) Abdominal tergite VIII; (18) Abdominal tergite V; (19) Abdominal tergite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920164/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); tergites III–VI with setae S3 positioned well ahead of posterior margin, with 2–3 setae lateral to S3 (
<figureCitation box="[404,630,582,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–19" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–19. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (13) Female abdominal tergites IX–X; (14) Abdominal tergite III; (15) Abdominal tergite VI; (16) Pore plate on male abdominal sternites VI–VII; (17) Abdominal tergite VIII; (18) Abdominal tergite V; (19) Abdominal tergite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920164/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Figs 14, 15, 18 &amp; 19</figureCitation>
); tergite IX with 2 pairs of mid-dorsal setae (
<figureCitation box="[1118,1198,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–19" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–19. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (13) Female abdominal tergites IX–X; (14) Abdominal tergite III; (15) Abdominal tergite VI; (16) Pore plate on male abdominal sternites VI–VII; (17) Abdominal tergite VIII; (18) Abdominal tergite V; (19) Abdominal tergite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920164/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Abdominal sternites without discal setae; III–VI completely covered with discal microtrichia, posterior margin with complete comb of microtrichia interrupted only at setal bases, posteromarginal setae at sternite VII arising in front of posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,691,717]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Measurements</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[388,488,691,717]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">holotype</typeStatus>
female in microns). Body length 920. Head, length 90; width across eyes 140; ocellar setae III 10; postocular setae I 10. Pronotum, length 95; width 175; pronotal blotch length (50 median, 70 lateral); width 140. Metanotum median setae length 25. Fore wing length 600. Antennal segments III–VIII length 50, 45, 35, 45, 10, 10.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,406,834,861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Male macroptera.</emphasis>
Similar to female, but smaller in size (
<figureCitation box="[858,928,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-71@3.[151,1435,344,1778]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–12. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (5) Female; (6) Male; (7) Meso and metanotum; (8) Head, dorsal; (9) Pronotum; (10) Fore wing; (11) Metasternum; (12) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920158/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); sternites VI–VII with elongated transverse pore plate (
<figureCitation box="[278,361,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–19" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1387,1411]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[151,1435,524,1364]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–19. Hydatothrips initium sp.n. (13) Female abdominal tergites IX–X; (14) Abdominal tergite III; (15) Abdominal tergite VI; (16) Pore plate on male abdominal sternites VI–VII; (17) Abdominal tergite VIII; (18) Abdominal tergite V; (19) Abdominal tergite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6920164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6920164/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,907,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">Measurements</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[389,487,907,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="179">paratype</typeStatus>
male in microns). Body length 660. Head, length 60; width across eyes 135; ocellar setae III 10; postocular setae I 10. Pronotum, length 80; width 160; pronotal blotch length (45 median, 60 lateral); width 125. Metanotum median setae length 25. Fore wing length 550. Antennal segments III–VIII length 45, 40, 35, 40, 5, 10.
</paragraph>
